1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO PROTECT NORTH CAROLINIANS BY ENACTING THE PERSONAL DATA
3 PRIVACY ACT AND SOCIAL MEDIA SAFETY ACT.
4 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
5
6 PART I. ENACT PERSONAL DATA PRIVACY ACT
7 SECTION 1.1. This Part shall be known and may be cited as the "North Carolina
8 Personal Data Privacy Act."
9 SECTION 1.2. Effective January 1, 2026, the General Statutes are amended by
10 adding a new Chapter to read:
11 "Chapter 75F.
12 "Data Privacy Act.
13 "§ 75F-101. Short title.
14 This Chapter shall be known and may be cited as the "North Carolina Data Privacy Act."
15 "§ 75F-102. Definitions.
16 The following definitions apply in this Chapter:
17 (1) Affiliate. – A legal entity that shares common branding with another legal
18 entity or controls, is controlled by, or is under common control with another
19 legal entity. For the purposes of this subdivision, "control" or "controlled"
20 means any of the following:
21 a. Ownership of, or the power to vote, more than fifty percent (50%) of
22 the outstanding shares of any class of voting security of a legal entity.
23 b. Control in any manner over the election of a majority of the directors
24 or of individuals exercising similar functions.
25 c. The power to exercise controlling influence over the management of a
26 legal entity.
27 (2) Authenticate. – To use reasonable means to determine that a request to
28 exercise any of the rights afforded under G.S. 75F-104(a)(1) to (4), inclusive,
29 is being made by, or on behalf of, the consumer who is entitled to exercise the
30 consumer rights with respect to the personal data at issue.
31 (3) Biometric data. – Personal information and data generated by automatic
32 measurements of an individual's unique biological characteristics, such as a
33 fingerprint, a voiceprint, eye retinas, irises, or other unique biological patterns
34 or characteristics that can be used to identify or authenticate a specific
35 individual. "Biometric data" does not include any of the following:
36 a. A digital or physical photograph.
*H462-v-2*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 b. An audio or video recording.
2 c. Any data generated from a digital or physical photograph, or an audio
3 or video recording, unless the data is generated to identify a specific
4 individual.
5 (4) Child. – As defined in COPPA.
6 (5) Child abuse. – Any conduct that would make an individual under 18 years of
7 age qualify as an abused juvenile under G.S. 7B-101 or any equivalent
8 provision in the laws of any other state; the United States; any territory,
9 district, or subdivision of the United States; or any foreign jurisdiction.
10 (6) Consent. – A clear affirmative act signifying a consumer's freely given,
11 specific, informed, and unambiguous agreement to allow the processing of
12 personal data relating to the consumer. "Consent" may include a written
13 statement, including by electronic means, or any other unambiguous
14 affirmative action. "Consent" does not include any of the following:
15 a. Acceptance of a general or broad terms of use or similar document that
16 contains descriptions of personal data processing along with other,
17 unrelated information.
18 b. Hovering over, muting, pausing, or closing a given piece of content.
19 c. Agreement obtained through the use of dark patterns.
20 (7) Consumer. – An individual who is a resident of this State. "Consumer" does
21 not include an individual acting in a commercial or employment context or as
22 an employee, owner, director, officer, or contractor of a company, partnership,
23 sole proprietorship, nonprofit organization, or government agency whose
24 communications or transactions with the controller occur solely within the
25 context of that individual's role with the company, partnership, sole
26 proprietorship, nonprofit organization, or government agency.
27 (8) Controller. – A person that, alone or jointly with others, determines the
28 purpose and means of processing personal data.
29 (9) COPPA. – The Children's Online Privacy Protection Act of 1998, 15 U.S.C.
30 § 6501, et seq., as amended, and the regulations, rules, guidance, and
31 exemptions adopted pursuant to the act, and such regulations, rules, guidance,
32 and exemptions as may be amended.
33 (10) Dark pattern. – Any of the following:
34 a. A user interface designed or manipulated with the substantial effect of
35 subverting or impairing user autonomy, decision making, or choice.
36 b. Any other practice the Federal Trade Commission refers to as a dark
37 pattern.
38 (11) Decisions that produce legal or similarly significant effects concerning the
39 consumer. – Decisions made by the controller that result in the provision or
40 denial by the controller of financial or lending services, housing, insurance,
41 education enrollment or opportunity, criminal justice, employment
42 opportunities, health care services, or access to essential goods or services.
43 (12) De-identified data. – Data that cannot reasonably be used to infer information
44 about, or otherwise be linked to, an identified or identifiable individual, or a
45 device linked to the individual, if the controller that possesses the data does
46 all of the following:
47 a. Takes reasonable measures to ensure that the data cannot be associated
48 with an individual.
49 b. Publicly commits to process the data only in a de-identified fashion
50 and not attempt to re-identify the data.
Page 2 House Bill 462-Second Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 c. Contractually obligates any recipients of the data to comply with all of
2 the provisions of this Chapter applicable to the controller with respect
3 to the data.
4 (13) Domestic violence. – As defined in G.S. 14-32.5 or any equivalent provision
5 in the laws of any other state; the United States; any territory, district, or
6 subdivision of the United States; or any foreign jurisdiction.
7 (14) Genetic data. – Any data, regardless of its format, that results from the analysis
8 of a biological sample of an individual, or from another source enabling
9 equivalent information to be obtained, and concerns genetic material. For
10 purposes of this subdivision, "genetic material" includes deoxyribonucleic
11 acids (DNA), ribonucleic acids (RNA), genes, chromosomes, alleles,
12 genomes, alterations or modifications to DNA or RNA, single nucleotide
13 polymorphisms (SNPs), uninterpreted data that results from analysis of the
14 biological sample or other source, and any information extrapolated, derived,
15 or inferred therefrom.
16 (15) HIPAA. – The Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act of 1996,
17 42 U.S.C. § 1320d, et seq., as amended.
18 (16) Human trafficking. – The offense defined in G.S. 14-43.11 or any equivalent
19 provision in the laws of any other state; the United States; any territory,
20 district, or subdivision of the United States; or any foreign jurisdiction.
21 (17) Identified or identifiable individual. – An individual who can be readily
22 identified, directly or indirectly.
23 (18) Nonprofit organization. – Any organization that is exempt from taxation under
24 section 501(c)(3), 501(c)(4), 501(c)(6), or 501(c)(12) of the Internal Revenue
25 Code of 1986, or any subsequent corresponding internal revenue code of the
26 United States, as amended.
27 (19) Personal data. – Any information that is linked or reasonably linkable to an
28 identified or identifiable individual and does not include de-identified data or
29 publicly available information.
30 (20) Precise geolocation data. – Information derived from technology, including
31 global positioning system level latitude and longitude coordinates or other
32 mechanisms, that directly identifies the specific location of an individual with
33 precision and accuracy within a radius of 1,750 feet. "Precise geolocation
34 data" does not include the content of communications or any data generated
35 by or connected to advanced utility metering infrastructure systems or
36 equipment for use by a utility.
37 (21) Process or processing. – Any operation or set of operations performed,
38 whether by manual or automated means, on personal data or on sets of
39 personal data, such as the collection, use, storage, disclosure, analysis,
40 deletion, or modification of personal data.
41 (22) Processor. – A person that processes personal data on behalf of a controller.
42 (23) Profiling. – Any form of automated processing performed on personal data to
43 evaluate, analyze, or predict personal aspects related to an identified or
44 identifiable individual's economic situation, health, demographic
45 characteristics, personal preferences, interests, reliability, behavior, location,
46 or movements.
47 (24) Pseudonymous data. – Personal data that cannot be attributed to a specific
48 individual without the use of additional information, provided the additional
49 information is kept separately and is subject to appropriate technical and
50 organizational measures to ensure that the personal data is not attributed to an
51 identified or identifiable individual.
