1 c. Advertisements directed to a consumer in direct response to the
2 consumer's request for information or feedback.
3 d. Processing personal data solely to measure or report advertising
4 frequency, performance, or reach.
5 (31) Third party. – With respect to personal data controlled by a controller, any
6 person other than the relevant consumer, the controller of the personal data,
7 or a processor or an affiliate of the processor or the controller.
8 (32) Trade secret. – As defined in Chapter 66, 95, or 113 of the General Statutes.
9 (33) Violent felony. – As defined in G.S. 14-7.7 and includes any equivalent
10 provision in the laws of any other state; the United States; any territory,
11 district, or subdivision of the United States; or any foreign jurisdiction.
12 "§ 75F-103. Applicability of Chapter.
13 (a) This Chapter applies to persons that conduct business in the State or persons that
14 produce products or services that are targeted to residents of the State and that during the
15 preceding calendar year did any of the following:
16 (1) Controlled or processed the personal data of not less than 35,000 consumers,
17 excluding personal data controlled or processed solely for the purpose of
18 completing a payment transaction.
19 (2) Controlled or processed the personal data of not less than 10,000 consumers
20 and derived more than twenty percent (20%) of their gross revenue from the
21 sale of personal data.
22 (b) This Chapter does not apply to any of the following entities:
23 (1) Any regulatory, administrative, advisory, executive, appointive, legislative, or
24 judicial body of the State or a political subdivision of the State, including any
25 board, bureau, commission, or agency of the State or a political subdivision
26 of the State, but excluding any institution of higher education.
27 (2) Any financial institution or affiliate of a financial institution governed by, or
28 personal data collected, processed, or disclosed in accordance with, Title V of
29 the Gramm-Leach-Bliley Act, 15 U.S.C. § 6801, et seq., and related
30 regulations.
31 (c) This Chapter does not apply to the following information and data:
32 (1) Protected health information as defined in 45 C.F.R. § 160.103.
33 (2) Patient-identifying information for purposes of 42 U.S.C. § 290dd-2.
34 (3) Identifiable private information, as defined in 45 C.F.R. § 46.102, to the extent
35 that it is used for purposes of the federal policy for the protection of human
36 subjects pursuant to 45 C.F.R. § 46.
37 (4) Identifiable private information to the extent it is collected and used as part of
38 human subjects research pursuant to the ICH E6 Good Clinical Practice
39 Guideline issued by the International Council for Harmonisation of Technical
40 Requirements for Pharmaceuticals for Human Use or the protection of human
41 subjects under 21 C.F.R. §§ 50 and 56.
42 (5) Patient safety work product, as defined in 42 C.F.R. § 3.20, that is created and
43 used for purposes of patient safety improvement pursuant to 42 C.F.R. § 3,
44 established pursuant to 42 U.S.C. §§ 299b–21 to 299b–26.
45 (6) Information to the extent it is used for public health, community health, or
46 population health activities and purposes, as authorized by HIPAA, when
47 provided by or to a Covered Entity, as defined in 45 C.F.R. § 160.103, or when
48 provided by or to a Business Associate, as defined in 45 C.F.R. § 160.103,
49 pursuant to a Business Associate Agreement with a Covered Entity.
50 (7) The collection, maintenance, disclosure, sale, communication, or use of any
51 personal information bearing on a consumer's credit worthiness, credit
