38 "§ 75F-104. Consumer personal data rights.
39 (a) A consumer has the right to do all of the following:
40 (1) Confirm whether a controller is processing the consumer's personal data and
41 access the personal data, unless the confirmation or access would require the
42 controller to reveal a trade secret.
43 (2) Correct inaccuracies in the consumer's personal data, taking into account the
44 nature of the personal data and the purposes of the processing of the
45 consumer's personal data.
46 (3) Have personal data provided by, or obtained about, the consumer deleted.
47 (4) Obtain a copy of the consumer's personal data processed by the controller, in
48 a portable and, to the extent technically feasible, readily usable format that
49 allows the consumer to transmit the data to another controller without
50 hindrance, where the processing is carried out by automated means, provided
51 the controller shall not be required to reveal any trade secret.
Page 6 House Bill 462-Second Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (5) Obtain a list of the specific third parties to which the controller has disclosed
2 the consumer's personal data. If the controller does not maintain this
3 information in a format specific to the consumer, a list of specific third parties
4 to whom the controller has disclosed any consumers' personal data may be
5 provided instead.
6 (6) Opt out of the processing of the personal data for purposes of any of the
7 following:
8 a. Targeted advertising.
9 b. The sale of personal data, except as provided in G.S. 75F-106(b).
10 c. Profiling in furtherance of solely automated decisions that produce
11 legal or similarly significant effects concerning the consumer.
12 (b) A consumer may exercise rights under this section by secure and reliable means
13 established by the controller and described to the consumer in the controller's privacy notice. A
14 consumer may designate an authorized agent in accordance with G.S. 75F-105 to exercise the
15 rights of the consumer to opt out of the processing of the consumer's personal data for purposes
16 of subdivision (6) of subsection (a) of this section on behalf of the consumer. In the case of
17 processing personal data of a known child, the parent or legal guardian may exercise the
18 consumer rights on the child's behalf. In the case of processing personal data concerning a
19 consumer subject to a guardianship, conservatorship, or other protective arrangement, the
20 guardian or the conservator of the consumer may exercise the rights on the consumer's behalf.
21 (c) Except as otherwise provided in this Chapter, a controller shall comply with a request
22 by a consumer to exercise the consumer rights authorized pursuant to said sections as follows:
23 (1) A controller shall respond to the consumer without undue delay but not later
24 than 45 days after receipt of the request. The controller may extend the
25 response period by 45 additional days when reasonably necessary, considering
26 the complexity and number of the consumer's requests, provided the controller
27 informs the consumer of any such extension within the initial 45-day response
28 period and of the reason for the extension.
29 (2) If a controller declines to take action regarding the consumer's request, the
30 controller shall inform the consumer without undue delay but not later than 45
31 days after receipt of the request of the justification for declining to take action
32 and instructions for how to appeal the decision.
33 (3) Information provided in response to a consumer request shall be provided by
34 a controller, free of charge, once per consumer during any 12-month period.
35 If requests from a consumer are manifestly unfounded, excessive, or
36 repetitive, the controller may charge the consumer a reasonable fee to cover
37 the administrative costs of complying with the request or decline to act on the
38 request. The controller bears the burden of demonstrating the manifestly
39 unfounded, excessive, or repetitive nature of the request.
40 (4) If a controller is unable to authenticate a request to exercise any of the rights
41 afforded under subdivisions (1) through (5), inclusive, of subsection (a) of this
42 section using commercially reasonable efforts, the controller shall not be
43 required to comply with a request to initiate an action pursuant to this section
44 and shall provide notice to the consumer that the controller is unable to
45 authenticate the request to exercise the right or rights until the consumer
46 provides additional information reasonably necessary to authenticate the
47 consumer and the consumer's request to exercise the right or rights. A
48 controller shall not be required to authenticate an opt-out request, but a
49 controller may deny an opt-out request if the controller has a good-faith,
50 reasonable, and documented belief that the request is fraudulent. If a controller
51 denies an opt-out request because the controller believes the request is
House Bill 462-Second Edition Page 7

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 fraudulent, the controller shall send a notice to the person who made the
2 request disclosing that the controller believes the request is fraudulent, why
3 the controller believes the request is fraudulent, and that the controller shall
4 not comply with the request.
5 (5) A controller that has obtained personal data about a consumer from a source
6 other than the consumer shall be deemed in compliance with a consumer's
7 request to delete the data pursuant to subdivision (3) of subsection (a) of this
8 section if the controller retains a record of the deletion request and the
9 minimum data necessary for the purpose of ensuring the consumer's personal
10 data remains deleted from the controller's records and does not use the retained
11 data for any other purpose.
12 (d) A controller shall establish a process for a consumer to appeal the controller's refusal
13 to take action on a request within a reasonable period of time after the consumer's receipt of the
14 decision. The appeal process shall be conspicuously available and similar to the process for
15 submitting requests to initiate action pursuant to this section. Not later than 60 days after receipt
16 of an appeal, a controller shall inform the consumer in writing of any action taken or not taken
17 in response to the appeal, including a written explanation of the reasons for the decisions. If the
18 appeal is denied, the controller shall also provide the consumer with an online mechanism, if
19 available, or other method through which the consumer may contact the Department of Justice
20 to submit a complaint.
21 "§ 75F-105. Designation of agent to exercise rights of consumer, including through
22 universal opt-out mechanisms.
23 (a) A consumer may designate an authorized agent to act on the consumer's behalf to opt
24 out of the processing of the consumer's personal data for one or more of the purposes specified
25 in G.S. 75F-104(a)(6). The consumer may designate the authorized agent by way of, among other
26 things, a platform, technology, or mechanism, including an internet link or a browser setting,
27 browser extension, or global device setting, indicating the consumer's intent to opt out of the
28 processing. For the purposes of the designation, the platform, technology, or mechanism may
29 function as the agent for purposes of conveying the consumer's decision to opt out.
30 (b) A controller shall comply with an opt-out request received from an authorized agent
31 if the controller is able to verify, with commercially reasonable effort, the identity of the
32 consumer and the authorized agent's authority to act on the consumer's behalf. The North
33 Carolina Department of Justice may publish or reference on its website a list of agents who
34 presumptively shall have the authority unless the controller has established a reasonable basis to
35 conclude that the agent lacks such authority.
36 "§ 75F-106. Duties of controllers.
37 (a) A controller shall do all of the following:
38 (1) Limit the collection of personal data to what is adequate, relevant, and
39 reasonably necessary in relation to the purposes for which the data is
40 processed, as disclosed to the consumer.
41 (2) Except as otherwise permitted by this Chapter, not process personal data for
42 purposes that are neither reasonably necessary to, nor compatible with, the
43 disclosed purposes for which the personal data is processed, as disclosed to
44 the consumer, unless the controller obtains the consumer's consent.
45 (3) Establish, implement, and maintain reasonable administrative, technical, and
46 physical data security practices to protect the confidentiality, integrity, and
47 accessibility of personal data appropriate to the volume and nature of the
48 personal data at issue.
49 (4) Not process sensitive data concerning a consumer without obtaining the
50 consumer's consent or, in the case of the processing of sensitive data
Page 8 House Bill 462-Second Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 concerning a known child, without first obtaining consent from the child's
2 parent or lawful guardian.
3 (5) Not process personal data in violation of the laws of this State and federal laws
4 that prohibit unlawful discrimination.
5 (6) Provide an effective mechanism for a consumer to revoke the consumer's
6 consent under this section that is at least as easy as the mechanism by which
7 the consumer provided the consumer's consent and, upon revocation of the
8 consent, cease to process the data as soon as practicable but not later than 15
9 days after the receipt of the request.
10 (7) Not process the personal data of a consumer for purposes of targeted
11 advertising, or sell the consumer's personal data without the consumer's
12 consent, under circumstances where a controller has actual knowledge or
13 willfully disregards that the consumer is at least 13 years of age but younger
14 than 18 years of age.
15 (8) Not discriminate against a consumer for exercising any of the consumer rights
16 contained in this Chapter, including denying goods or services, charging
17 different prices or rates for goods or services, or providing a different level of
18 quality of goods or services to the consumer.
19 (b) Nothing in subsection (a) of this section shall be construed to require a controller to
20 provide a product or service that requires the personal data of a consumer which the controller
21 does not collect or maintain, or prohibit a controller from offering a different price, rate, level,
22 quality, or selection of goods or services to a consumer, including offering goods or services for
23 no fee, if the offering is in connection with a consumer's voluntary participation in a bona fide
24 loyalty, rewards, premium features, discounts, or club card program.
25 (c) A controller shall provide consumers with a reasonably accessible, clear, and
26 meaningful privacy notice that includes all of the following:
27 (1) The categories of personal data processed by the controller.
28 (2) The purpose for processing personal data.
29 (3) How consumers may exercise their consumer rights, including how a
30 consumer may appeal a controller's decision with regard to the consumer's
31 request.
32 (4) The categories of personal data that the controller shares with third parties, if
33 any.
34 (5) The categories of third parties with which the controller shares personal data,
35 if any.
36 (6) An active electronic mail address or other online mechanism that the
37 consumer may use to contact the controller.
38 (d) If a controller sells personal data to third parties or processes personal data for targeted
39 advertising, the controller shall clearly and conspicuously disclose the processing, as well as the
40 manner in which a consumer may exercise the right to opt out of the processing.
41 (e) A controller shall establish and shall describe in the privacy notice required by
42 subsection (c) of this section one or more secure and reliable means for consumers to submit a
43 request to exercise their consumer rights pursuant to this Chapter. The means shall take into
44 account the ways in which consumers normally interact with the controller, the need for secure
45 and reliable communication of the requests, and the ability of the controller to verify the identity
46 of the consumer making the request. A controller shall not require a consumer to create a new
47 account in order to exercise consumer rights but may require a consumer to use an existing
48 account. Any such means shall include all of the following:
49 (1) Providing a clear and conspicuous link on the controller's internet website to
50 an internet webpage that enables a consumer, or an agent of the consumer, to
51 opt out of the targeted advertising or the sale of the consumer's personal data.
