5 consumer's intent to opt out of any such processing or sale. The platform,
6 technology, or mechanism shall do all of the following:
7 a. Not unfairly disadvantage another controller.
8 b. Not make use of a default setting but, rather, require the consumer to
9 make an affirmative, freely given, and unambiguous choice to opt out
10 of any processing of the consumer's personal data pursuant to this
11 Chapter.
12 c. Be consumer-friendly and easy to use by the average consumer.
13 d. Be as consistent as possible with any other similar platform,
14 technology, or mechanism required by any federal or State law or
15 regulation.
16 e. Enable the controller to reasonably determine whether the consumer
17 is a resident of the State and whether the consumer has made a
18 legitimate request to opt out of any sale of the consumer's personal
19 data or targeted advertising.
20 (f) If a consumer's decision to opt out of any processing of the consumer's personal data
21 for the purposes of targeted advertising, or any sale of the personal data, through an opt-out
22 preference signal sent in accordance with the provisions of subdivision (1) of this subsection
23 conflicts with the consumer's existing controller-specific privacy setting or voluntary
24 participation in a controller's bona fide loyalty, rewards, premium features, discounts, or club
25 card program, the controller shall comply with the consumer's opt-out preference signal but may
26 notify the consumer of the conflict and provide to the consumer the choice to confirm the
27 controller-specific privacy setting or participation in the program.
28 (g) If a controller responds to consumer opt‐out requests received pursuant to subdivision
29 (1) of this subsection by informing the consumer of a charge for the use of any product or service,
30 the controller shall present the terms of any financial incentive offered pursuant to subdivision
31 (2) of this subsection for the retention, use, sale, or sharing of the consumer's personal data.
32 "§ 75F-107. Duties of processors.
33 (a) A processor shall adhere to the instructions of a controller and shall assist the
34 controller in meeting the controller's obligations under this Chapter. The assistance must include
35 all of the following:
36 (1) Taking into account the nature of processing and the information available to
37 the processor, by appropriate technical and organizational measures, insofar
38 as is reasonably practicable, to fulfill the controller's obligation to respond to
39 consumer rights requests.
40 (2) Taking into account the nature of processing and the information available to
41 the processor, by assisting the controller in meeting the controller's obligations
42 in relation to the security of processing the personal data and in relation to the
43 notification of a breach of security of the system of the processor, in order to
44 meet the controller's obligations.
45 (3) Providing necessary information to enable the controller to conduct and
46 document data protection assessments.
47 (b) A contract between a controller and a processor must govern the processor's data
48 processing procedures with respect to processing performed on behalf of the controller. The
49 contract must be binding and clearly set forth instructions for processing data, the nature and
50 purpose of processing, the type of data subject to processing, the duration of processing, and the
Page 10 House Bill 462-Second Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 rights and obligations of both parties. The contract must also require that the processor do all of
2 the following:
3 (1) Ensure that each person processing personal data is subject to a duty of
4 confidentiality with respect to the data.
5 (2) At the controller's direction, delete or return all personal data to the controller
6 as requested at the end of the provision of services, unless retention of the
7 personal data is required by law.
8 (3) Upon the reasonable request of the controller, make available to the controller
9 all information in its possession necessary to demonstrate the processor's
10 compliance with the obligations in this Chapter.
11 (4) After providing the controller an opportunity to object, engage any
12 subcontractor pursuant to a written contract that requires the subcontractor to
13 meet the obligations of the processor with respect to the personal data.
14 (5) Allow, and cooperate with, reasonable assessments by the controller or the
15 controller's designated assessor, or the processor may arrange for a qualified
16 and independent assessor to conduct an assessment of the processor's policies
17 and technical and organizational measures in support of the obligations under
18 this Chapter, using an appropriate and accepted control standard or framework
19 and assessment procedure for the assessments. The processor shall provide a
20 report of the assessment to the controller upon request.
21 (c) Nothing in this section may be construed to relieve a controller or processor from the
22 liabilities imposed on the controller or processor by virtue of the controller's or processor's role
23 in the processing relationship, as described in this Chapter.
24 (d) Determining whether a person is acting as a controller or processor with respect to a
25 specific processing of data is a fact-based determination that depends upon the context in which
26 personal data is to be processed. A person who is not limited in the person's processing of
27 personal data pursuant to a controller's instructions, or who fails to adhere to the instructions, is
28 a controller and not a processor with respect to a specific processing of data. A processor that
29 continues to adhere to a controller's instructions with respect to a specific processing of personal
30 data remains a processor. If a processor begins, alone or jointly with others, determining the
31 purposes and means of the processing of personal data, the processor is a controller with respect
32 to the processing and may be subject to an enforcement action under this Chapter.
33 "§ 75F-108. Data protection assessments.
34 (a) A controller that controls or processes the data of not less than 100,000 consumers,
35 excluding data controlled or processed solely for the purpose of completing a payment
36 transaction, shall conduct and document, on a regular basis, a data protection assessment for each
37 of the controller's processing activities that presents a heightened risk of harm to a consumer. For
38 the purposes of this section, processing that presents a heightened risk of harm to a consumer
39 includes any of the following:
40 (1) The processing of personal data for the purposes of targeted advertising.
41 (2) The sale of personal data.
42 (3) The processing of personal data for the purposes of profiling, where the
43 profiling presents a reasonably foreseeable risk of any of the following:
44 a. Unfair or deceptive treatment of, or unlawful disparate impact on,
45 consumers.
46 b. Financial, physical, or reputational injury to consumers.
47 c. A physical or other intrusion upon the solitude or seclusion, or the
48 private affairs or concerns, of consumers, where the intrusion would
49 be offensive to a reasonable person.
50 d. Other substantial injury to consumers.
51 (4) The processing of sensitive data.
House Bill 462-Second Edition Page 11

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (b) Data protection assessments conducted pursuant to subsection (a) of this section shall
2 identify and weigh the benefits that may flow, directly and indirectly, from the processing to the
3 controller, the consumer, other stakeholders, and the public against the potential risks to the rights
4 of the consumer associated with the processing, as mitigated by safeguards that can be employed
5 by the controller to reduce the risks. The controller shall factor into any such data protection
6 assessment the use of de-identified data and the reasonable expectations of consumers, as well
7 as the context of the processing and the relationship between the controller and the consumer
8 whose personal data will be processed.
9 (c) The Attorney General may require that a controller disclose any data protection
10 assessment that is relevant to an investigation conducted by the Attorney General, and the
11 controller shall make the data protection assessment available to the Attorney General. The
12 Attorney General may evaluate the data protection assessment for compliance with the
13 responsibilities set forth in this Chapter. Data protection assessments must be treated as
14 confidential and are not public records within the meaning of Chapter 132 of the General Statutes.
15 Notwithstanding the foregoing, a controller's data protection assessment may be used in an action
16 to enforce this Chapter. To the extent any information contained in a data protection assessment
17 disclosed to the Attorney General includes and conspicuously identifies information subject to
18 attorney-client privilege or work product protection, the disclosure by itself does not constitute a
19 waiver of the privilege or protection.
20 (d) A single data protection assessment may address a comparable set of processing
21 operations that include similar activities.
22 (e) If a controller conducts a data protection assessment for the purpose of complying
23 with another applicable law or regulation, the data protection assessment shall be deemed to
24 satisfy the requirements established in this section if the data protection assessment is reasonably
25 similar in scope and effect to the data protection assessment that would otherwise be conducted
26 pursuant to this section.
27 "§ 75F-109. De-identified data.
28 (a) Nothing in this Chapter shall be construed to require a controller or processor to
29 re-identify de-identified data or pseudonymous data, or to maintain data in identifiable form, or
30 collect, obtain, retain, or access any data or technology, in order to be capable of associating an
31 authenticated consumer request with personal data.
32 (b) Nothing in this Chapter shall be construed to require a controller or processor to
33 comply with an authenticated consumer rights request if all of the following apply:
34 (1) The controller is not reasonably capable of associating the request with the
35 personal data or it would be unreasonably burdensome for the controller to
36 associate the request with the personal data.
37 (2) The controller does not use the personal data to recognize or respond to the
38 specific consumer who is the subject of the personal data or associate the
39 personal data with other personal data about the same specific consumer.
40 (3) The controller does not sell the personal data to any third party or otherwise
41 voluntarily disclose the personal data to any third party other than a processor,
42 except as otherwise permitted in this section.
43 (c) The rights afforded under G.S. 75F-104(a)(1) to (4), inclusive, do not apply to
44 pseudonymous data in cases where the controller is able to demonstrate that any information
45 necessary to identify the consumer is kept separately and is subject to effective technical and
46 organizational controls that prevent the controller from accessing the information.
47 (d) A controller that discloses pseudonymous data or de-identified data shall exercise
48 reasonable oversight to monitor compliance with any contractual commitments to which the
49 pseudonymous data or de-identified data is subject and shall take appropriate steps to address
50 any breaches of those contractual commitments. The determination of the reasonableness of the
Page 12 House Bill 462-Second Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 oversight and the appropriateness of contractual enforcement must take into account whether the
2 disclosed data includes data that would be sensitive data if it were re-identified.
3 "§ 75F-110. Exclusions.
4 (a) Nothing in this Chapter shall be construed to restrict a controller's or processor's
5 ability to do any of the following:
6 (1) Comply with federal, State, or local laws, rules, or regulations.
7 (2) Comply with a civil, criminal, or regulatory inquiry, investigation, subpoena,
8 or summons by federal, State, local, or other governmental authorities.
9 (3) Cooperate with law enforcement agencies concerning conduct or activity that
10 the controller or processor reasonably and in good faith believes may violate
11 federal, State, or local laws, rules, or regulations.
12 (4) Investigate, establish, exercise, prepare for, or defend legal claims.
13 (5) Provide a product or service specifically requested by a consumer.
14 (6) Perform under a contract to which a consumer is a party, including fulfilling
15 the terms of a written warranty.
16 (7) Take steps at the request of a consumer prior to entering into a contract.
17 (8) Take immediate steps to protect an interest that is essential for the life or
18 physical safety of the consumer or another individual and where the
19 processing cannot be manifestly based on another legal basis.
20 (9) Prevent, detect, protect against, or respond to security incidents, identity theft,
21 fraud, harassment, malicious or deceptive activities, or any illegal activity;
22 preserve the integrity or security of systems; or investigate, report, or
23 prosecute those responsible for any such activity.
24 (10) Engage in public or peer-reviewed scientific research in the public interest that
25 adheres to all other applicable ethics and privacy laws and is approved,
26 monitored, and governed by an institutional review board that determines
27 whether the deletion of the information is likely to provide substantial benefits
28 that do not exclusively accrue to the controller, the expected benefits of the
29 research outweigh the privacy risks, and whether the controller has
30 implemented reasonable safeguards to mitigate privacy risks associated with
31 research, including any risks associated with re-identification.
32 (11) Assist another controller, processor, or third party with any of the activities
33 under this subsection.
34 (b) The obligations imposed on controllers or processors under this Chapter, other than
35 those imposed by G.S. 75F-109, do not restrict a controller's or processor's ability to collect data
36 directly from consumers, or use or retain the data, for internal use only, to do any of the following:
37 (1) Conduct internal research to develop, improve, or repair products, services, or
38 technology.
39 (2) Effectuate a product recall.
40 (3) Identify and repair technical errors that impair existing or intended
41 functionality.
42 (4) Perform internal operations that are reasonably aligned with the expectations
43 of the consumer or reasonably anticipated based on the consumer's existing
44 relationship with the controller or are otherwise compatible with processing
45 data in furtherance of the provision of a product or service specifically
46 requested by a consumer or the performance of a contract to which the
47 consumer is a party.
48 (c) The obligations imposed on controllers or processors under this Chapter shall not
49 apply where compliance by the controller or processor with said sections would violate an
50 evidentiary privilege under the laws of this State. Nothing in this Chapter shall be construed to
51 prevent a controller or processor from providing personal data concerning a consumer to a person
House Bill 462-Second Edition Page 13

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 covered by an evidentiary privilege under the laws of this State as part of a privileged
2 communication.
3 (d) A controller or processor that discloses personal data to a processor or third-party
4 controller in compliance with this Chapter shall not be deemed to have violated said sections if
5 the processor or third-party controller that receives and processes the personal data violates said
6 sections, provided that (i) at the time the disclosing controller or processor disclosed the personal
7 data, the disclosing controller or processor did not have actual knowledge that the receiving
8 processor or third-party controller had violated or would violate said sections and (ii) the
9 disclosing controller or processor was, and remained, in compliance with its obligations as the
10 discloser of the data hereunder. A third-party controller or processor receiving personal data from
11 a controller or processor in compliance with this Chapter is likewise not in violation of said
12 sections for the independent misconduct of the controller or processor from which the third-party
13 controller or processor receives the personal data.
14 (e) Nothing in this Chapter may be construed to do any of the following:
15 (1) Impose any obligation on a controller or processor that adversely affects the
16 rights of any person to freedom of speech or freedom of the press guaranteed
17 by the First Amendment to the United States Constitution or Article I, Section
18 14 of the North Carolina Constitution.
19 (2) Apply to any person's processing of personal data in the course of the person's
20 purely personal or household activities.
21 (f) Personal data processed pursuant to this section may be processed to the extent that
22 the processing is reasonably necessary and proportionate to the purposes listed in this section and
23 is adequate, relevant, and limited to what is necessary in relation to the specific purposes listed
24 in this section. Personal data collected, used, or retained pursuant to subsection (b) of this section
25 shall, where applicable, take into account the nature and purpose or purposes of the collection,
26 use, or retention. The data shall be subject to reasonable administrative, technical, and physical
27 measures to protect the confidentiality, integrity, and accessibility of the personal data and to
28 reduce reasonably foreseeable risks of harm to consumers relating to the collection, use, or
29 retention of personal data.
30 (g) If a controller processes personal data pursuant to an exemption in this section, the
31 controller bears the burden of demonstrating that the processing qualifies for the exemption and
32 complies with the requirements of subsection (f) of this section.
33 (h) Processing personal data for the purposes expressly identified in this section shall not
34 solely make a legal entity a controller with respect to the processing.
35 "§ 75F-111. Enforcement.
36 (a) The North Carolina Department of Justice shall investigate and enforce alleged
37 violations of this Chapter.
38 (b) The North Carolina Department of Justice may, prior to initiating any action for a
39 violation of any provision of this Chapter, issue a notice of violation to the controller or processor
40 if the Department of Justice determines that a cure is possible. If the North Carolina Department
41 of Justice issues a notice of violation, the controller shall have at least 60 days to cure the violation
42 after receipt of the notice. If the controller fails to cure the violation within the time period, the
43 North Carolina Department of Justice may bring an enforcement proceeding pursuant to
44 subsection (a) of this section. In determining whether to grant a controller or processor an
45 opportunity to cure an alleged violation, the North Carolina Department of Justice may consider
46 all of the following:
47 (1) The number of violations.
48 (2) The size and complexity of the controller or processor.
49 (3) The nature and extent of the controller's or processor's processing activities.
50 (4) The substantial likelihood of injury to the public.
51 (5) The safety of persons or property.
Page 14 House Bill 462-Second Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (6) Whether the alleged violation was likely caused by human or technical error.
2 (7) The extent to which the controller or processor has violated this or similar
3 laws in the past.
4 (c) Nothing in this Chapter shall be construed as providing the basis for, or be subject to,
5 a private right of action for violations of said sections or any other law.
6 (d) A violation of this Chapter shall be deemed an unfair practice under G.S. 75-1.1."
7 SECTION 1.3. Beginning no later than July 1, 2025, the North Carolina Department
8 of Justice shall engage in public outreach to educate consumers and the business community
9 about this Part. Data protection assessment requirements in G.S. 75F-108, as enacted by this Part,
10 shall apply to processing activities created or generated on or after July 1, 2026, and are not
11 retroactive.
