13 PART II. ENACT SOCIAL MEDIA SAFETY ACT
14 SECTION 2.1. Effective January 1, 2026, the General Statutes are amended by
15 adding a new Chapter to read:
16 "Chapter 75G.
17 "Social Media Verification.
18 "§ 75G-101. Definitions.
19 The following definitions apply in this Chapter:
20 (1) Account holder. – An individual who creates an account or a profile to use a
21 social media platform.
22 (2) Commercial entity. – A corporation, limited liability company, partnership,
23 limited partnership, sole proprietorship, or other legally recognized entity. The
24 term includes a third-party vendor.
25 (3) Digitized identification card. – A data file available on a mobile device that
26 has connectivity to the internet through a State-approved application that
27 allows the mobile device to download the data file from the Division of Motor
28 Vehicles that contains all of the data elements visible on the face and back of
29 a drivers license or identification card and displays the current status of the
30 drivers license or identification card, including valid, expired, cancelled,
31 suspended, revoked, active, or inactive.
32 (4) Minor. – An individual under 18 years of age.
33 (5) North Carolina user. – An individual who is a resident of the State of North
34 Carolina and who accesses or attempts to access a social media platform while
35 present in this State or who accesses or attempts to access a social media
36 platform while using a North Carolina Internet Protocol address.
37 (6) Reasonable age verification. – A method to confirm that a person seeking to
38 open an account social media platform is at least 18 years old.
39 (7) Social media company. – An online forum that allows an account holder to do
40 any of the following:
41 a. Create a public profile, establish an account, or register as a user for
42 the primary purpose of interacting socially with other profiles and
43 accounts.
44 b. Upload or create posts or content.
45 c. View posts or content of other account holders.
46 d. Interact with other account holders or users, including, without
47 limitation, establishing mutual connections through request and
48 acceptance.
49 (8) Social media company. – Does not include any of the following:
House Bill 462-Second Edition Page 15

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 a. A company that exclusively offers subscription content in which users
2 follow or subscribe unilaterally and whose platforms' primary purpose
3 is not social interaction.
4 b. A social media company that allows a user to generate short video
5 clips of dancing, voice overs, or other acts of entertainment in which
6 the primary purpose is not educational or informative.
7 c. A media company that exclusively offers interactive gaming, virtual
8 gaming, or an online service that allows the creation and uploading of
9 content for the purpose of interactive gaming, entertainment, or
10 associated entertainment, and any communication related to that
11 content.
12 d. A company that offers cloud storage services, enterprise cybersecurity
13 services, educational devices, or enterprise collaboration tools for
14 kindergarten through grade 12 (K-12) schools and derives less than
15 twenty-five percent (25%) of the company's revenue from operating a
16 social media platform, including games and advertising.
17 e. A company that provides career development opportunities, including
18 professional networking, job skills, learning certifications, and job
19 posting and application services.
20 (9) Social media platform. – A public or semipublic internet-based service or
21 application that has users in North Carolina and when the substantial function
22 of the service or application is to connect users in order to allow users to
23 interact socially with each other within the service or application; however, a
24 service or application that provides email or direct messaging shall not be
25 considered to be a social media platform on the basis of that function alone.
26 (10) Social media platform. – Does not include an online service, a website, or an
27 application if the predominant or exclusive function is any of the following:
28 a. Electronic mail.
29 b. Direct messaging consisting of messages, photos, or videos that are
30 sent between devices by electronic means if the direct messages meet
31 all of the following criteria:
32 1. Shared between the sender and the recipient or recipients.
33 2. Only visible to the sender and the recipient or recipients.
34 3. Are not posted publicly.
35 c. A streaming service that (i) provides only licensed media in a
36 continuous flow from the service, website, or application to the end
37 user and (ii) does not obtain a license to the media from a user or
38 account holder by agreement of the streaming service's terms of
39 service.
40 d. News, sports, entertainment, or other content that is preselected by the
41 provider and not user generated, including, if any chat, comment, or
42 interactive functionality that is provided is incidental to, directly
43 related to, or dependent upon provision of the content.
44 e. Online shopping or e-commerce, if the interaction with other users or
45 account holders is generally limited to any of the following:
46 1. The ability to post and comment on reviews.
47 2. The ability to display lists or collections of goods for sale or
48 wish lists.
49 3. Any other function that is focused on online shopping or
50 e-commerce rather than interaction between users or account
51 holders.
Page 16 House Bill 462-Second Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 f. Business-to-business software that is not accessible to the general
2 public.
3 g. Cloud storage.
4 h. Shared document collaboration.
5 i. Providing access to or interacting with data visualization platforms,
6 libraries, or hubs.
7 j. Permitting comments on a digital news website, if the news content is
8 posted only by the provider of the digital news website.
9 k. For the purpose of providing or obtaining technical support for the
10 social media company's social media platform, products, or services.
11 l. Academic or scholarly research.
12 m. Other research if (i) the majority of the content is posted or created by
13 the provider of the online service, website, or application and (ii) the
14 ability to chat, comment, or interact with other users is directly related
15 to the provider's content; provided that the service is a classified
16 advertising service that only permits the sale of goods and prohibits
17 the solicitation of personal services or that is used by and under the
18 direction of an educational entity, including, a learning management
19 system, student engagement program, and subject-specific or
20 skill-specific program.
21 (11) Social media platform. – Does not include a social media platform that is
22 controlled by a business entity that has generated less than one hundred
23 million dollars ($100,000,000) in annual gross revenue.
24 (12) User. – A person who has access to view all or some of the posts and content
25 on a social media platform but is not an account holder.
26 "§ 75G-102. Social media platforms; reasonable age verification methods; parental consent
27 required.
28 (a) A social media company shall not permit a North Carolina user who is a minor to be
29 an account holder on the social media company's social media platform unless the minor has the
30 express consent of a parent or legal guardian.
31 (b) A social media company shall use a commercial entity to perform reasonable age
32 verification to verify the age of the user before allowing a North Carolina user to be an account
33 holder on the social media company's social media platform. If the North Carolina user is a minor,
34 the social media company shall confirm that a minor has consent under this section to become
35 an account holder before allowing the North Carolina user to open the account.
36 (c) Reasonable age verification methods under this section include one of the following:
37 (1) Providing a digitized identification card, including a digital copy of a drivers
38 license issued by the Division of Motor Vehicles.
39 (2) Providing a government-issued identification.
40 (3) Any commercially reasonable age verification method.
41 "§ 75G-103. Liability for social media companies.
42 (a) A social media company that knowingly violates this Chapter is liable if the social
43 media company fails to perform a reasonable age verification.
44 (b) If a social media company performs a reasonable age verification, the social media
45 company shall not retain any identifying information of the individual after access to an account
46 on the social media platform has been granted.
47 (c) A violation of G.S. 75G-102 is a Class 1 misdemeanor. The district attorney for the
48 county where the North Carolina user resides may initiate a criminal proceeding against a social
49 media company that allegedly violates G.S. 75G-102.
50 (d) The Attorney General may initiate a civil enforcement action against a social media
51 company that allegedly commits a violation of G.S. 75G-102.
House Bill 462-Second Edition Page 17

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (e) A social media company that violates this Chapter is liable to an individual for either
2 of the following:
3 (1) A penalty of two thousand five hundred dollars ($2,500) per violation, court
4 costs, and reasonable attorneys' fees as ordered by the court.
5 (2) Damages resulting from a minor accessing a social media platform without
6 his or her parent's or legal guardian's consent, including court costs and
7 reasonable attorneys' fees as ordered by the court.
8 (f) This section does not apply to a news or public interest broadcast, website video,
9 report, or event or to cloud service providers, or affect the rights of a news-gathering
10 organization.
11 (g) An internet service provider, or any of its affiliates or subsidiaries, or search engines
12 shall not violate this Chapter solely by providing access, connection to or from a website, or other
13 information or content on the internet, or a facility, system, or network that is not under that
14 internet service provider's control, including transmission, downloading, intermediate storage,
15 access software, or other service that provides access or connectivity, to the extent the internet
16 service provider is not responsible for the creation of the content or the communication on a
17 social media platform.
18 "§ 75G-104. Liability for commercial entity.
19 (a) A commercial entity shall not retain any identifying information of an individual after
20 access to the social media platform has been granted.
21 (b) A commercial entity that is found to have knowingly retained identifying information
22 of an individual after access to the material is granted is liable to the individual for damages
23 resulting from the retention of the identifying information, including court costs and reasonable
24 attorneys' fees as ordered by the court."
25
26 PART III. SEVERABILITY
27 SECTION 3.1. If any provision of this act or the application thereof to any person
28 or circumstance is held invalid, the invalidity does not affect any other provision or application
29 of the act which can be given effect without the invalid provision or application and, to that end,
30 the provisions of this act are declared to be severable.
31
32 PART IV. EFFECTIVE DATE
33 SECTION 4.1. Except as otherwise provided, this act is effective when it becomes
34 law.
